children.name: Text
children.value: Now you can focus on La Isla. Securing the future of men, women, children!

children.name: Text
children.value: Prosperity has been nothing but trouble for us. Go see for yourself.

children.name: Text
children.value: My followers on that island are living in fear!

children.name: Text
children.value: The persecuted, the diaspora, flock to La Isla. We must shelter them.

children.name: Text
children.value: We need to be able to hold out should the Pyrphorians strike. Anything you can provide will help.

children.name: Text
children.value: I feel bad for asking. But these people come here pockets empty.

children.name: Text
children.value: This place, La Isla, can be a fortress of salvation to these people.

children.name: Text
children.value: I didn't know if I could trust you. But you have given these people hope, and a future.

children.name: Text
children.value: We must get the people what they need, before the Pyrphorians can break our supply lines.

children.name: Text
children.value: Your father was guilty. I was with him when he signed the contract.

children.name: Text
children.value: I wouldn't be surprised if the Pyrphorians pressured your father too.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Pyrphorians took Prosperity from us the moment that deal was signed.

children.name: Text
children.value: Helping you is too risky right now. My people need shelter from the Pyrphorian menace.

children.name: Text
children.value: We had no choice. The Pyrphorians coerced us into buying Prosperity from your father.

children.name: Text
children.value: Prosperity is so rich in natural resources. No wonder it is the source of all this conflict.

children.name: Text
children.value: We want to forge something new, break away from the old.

children.name: Text
children.value: I trust your Empire no more than the Pyrphorians. We are just pawns in their game.

children.name: Text
children.value: Break free of La Corona, only to land in the lap of these Pyrphorian devils.

children.name: Text
children.value: They will torch the whole city, if you try to meddle. I suggest setting up routine patrols!

children.name: Text
children.value: Then the fires begin. It is their warning. You must find these masks who walk with the devil!

children.name: Text
children.value: The scars the fire leaves behind do not heal fast.

children.name: Text
children.value: We need a dedicated team to police the arsonists.

children.name: Text
children.value: I don't think your sister likes me. But I have to keep fighting for what I believe in.

children.name: Text
children.value: With your patrols, we can catch the arsonists in the act.

children.name: Text
children.value: It is these arsonists turn to be afraid!

children.name: Text
children.value: The Pyrphorians work the weak to collapse. La Isla is their only hope of recovery.

children.name: Text
children.value: Have sympathy for the many who are sick. Exhausted from the mines and the oil pumps.

children.name: Text
children.value: There are many who struggle even to walk, cruelly made to work.

children.name: Text
children.value: This is becoming a crisis. I worry the sick may die if we do not give them beds and clean linen.

children.name: Text
children.value: Their homes were taken from them. Help them dream again.

children.name: Text
children.value: First La Corona, now the Pyrphorians. If we come through this with our lives, we'll be lucky.

children.name: Text
children.value: Take the sick and the weak from Prosperity to La Isla. Save them from a life of exploitation.

children.name: Text
children.value: I cannot watch my people struggling under the Pyrphorian yoke.

children.name: Text
children.value: We cannot rely on the old guard, they have given so much of their lives already.

children.name: Text
children.value: This shall be the moment our movement truly begins! New ideas, new energy!

children.name: Text
children.value: The young ones dream of something better. Better homes and a better life.

children.name: Text
children.value: Without somewhere to call home, it is over for them.

children.name: Text
children.value: These refugees, they have nowhere else to go.

children.name: Text
children.value: You have to learn to make what friends you can out here.

children.name: Text
children.value: I hate knowing Empire or La Corona could just come here and crush us.

children.name: Text
children.value: I'm sure your Queen wants to go charging in like a bull in a china shop. But good people still live on Prosperity.

children.name: Text
children.value: I don't plan to leave anyone behind.

children.name: Text
children.value: Keep the people moving. Now is not the time to stop and think.

children.name: Text
children.value: All of us sticking together. That is the best chance we have of defending ourselves.

children.name: Text
children.value: Even a modest fleet would give us independence.

children.name: Text
children.value: It is not on land, but on water, where we are vulnerable.

children.name: Text
children.value: Wow this ship is so beautiful!

children.name: Text
children.value: We shall name her after my brother, and pin a lock of his hair to the mast.

children.name: Text
children.value: Pyrphorian ships approach. I have never dealt with them face-to-face. What can they want?

children.name: Text
children.value: It is started—there's no going back. The Pyrphorians never give up.

children.name: Text
children.value: Everything we produce here, the Pyrphorians take.

children.name: Text
children.value: After the Pyrphorians come for the tithe, there is nothing left for us.

children.name: Text
children.value: The cat is out of the bag. Now they know you are involved.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Pyrphorian attack frightens them. Please, there must be room!

children.name: Text
children.value: My island too must be evacuated, it is no longer safe there.

children.name: Text
children.value: Many of my best were kidnapped. We have no hope of surviving without them.

children.name: Text
children.value: What if these people grow sick, they're going to need a hospital!

children.name: Text
children.value: My people's future is secure. They have you to thank for this.

children.name: Text
children.value: The contract…it is gone! The Pyrphorians must have stolen it during the attack. How did I fall for such a simple diversion!

children.name: Text
children.value: You are going to have to inflitrate the Pyrphorians if you want to find that contract. I'm sorry.

children.name: Text
children.value: You beat the Pyrphorians at their own game!

children.name: Text
children.value: If you can convince the Queen to listen, we can explain her.

children.name: Text
children.value: I would give you that stupid island, if only I had the contract to tear to pieces.

children.name: Text
children.value: We cannot thank you enough for preventing this war.

children.name: Text
children.value: With that contract, we are taking the Pyrphorians down from the inside.

children.name: Text
children.value: Prosperity is yours, take it! We have a new home now.

children.name: Text
children.value: Near Prosperity, the Pyrphorians would kill us on sight.

children.name: Text
children.value: At first I thought you were a spy of the Queen. Now I know your heart is in the right place.

children.name: Text
children.value: I can tell you where the contract is. After that it's down to you.

children.name: Text
children.value: Stay hidden, and you will succeed.

children.name: Text
children.value: The man I met was your Uncle? I thought he was a creep!

children.name: Text
children.value: I am sorry you had to go through all this just to have justice.

children.name: Text
children.value: Of course I will be a witness. After all you've done for us.

children.name: Text
children.value: With Prosperity off our hands, the Pyrphorians will leave us alone.

children.name: Text
children.value: Let me help you. I know I can make a difference.

children.name: Text
children.value: I will tell them everything I know.

children.name: Text
children.value: I don't need to take an oath to speak the truth.

children.name: Text
children.value: I hope as witness, I can prove the Pyrphorians were behind this deal, not us.

children.name: Text
children.value: I was certain it was your father that day, but now I know was wrong.

children.name: Text
children.value: Your majesty. Isabel Sarmento, at your service.

children.name: Text
children.value: We fight with you, no matter what.

children.name: Text
children.value: We can help you, just give us the sign.

children.name: Text
children.value: Exploit their supply lines! Small operations can have big rewards!

children.name: Text
children.value: Sabotage their supply lines! They rely on them as much as we do.

children.name: Text
children.value: There is no dent in their supply! We missed an opportunity!

children.name: Text
children.value: Ha, you did it! Without their precious fire they are nothing!

children.name: Text
children.value: You broke the chain! Now we are really somewhere.

children.name: Text
children.value: I never thought I would take the Empire's side!

children.name: Text
children.value: The Queen has promised to recognise our independence.

children.name: Text
children.value: I like Sir Archibald, he is a funny man.

children.name: Text
children.value: Of course we will take a stand beside you, if you are for freedom and justice!

children.name: Text
children.value: Now is the time for choosing sides. Just or unjust.

children.name: Text
children.value: We join on one condition, that like you we are free to write our own history.

children.name: Text
children.value: We are all the stronger for this.

children.name: Text
children.value: A small win, but we'll take it.

children.name: Text
children.value: I wanted to believe you'd come through.

children.name: Text
children.value: It takes courage to make a stand.

children.name: Text
children.value: I was right to trust you.

children.name: Text
children.value: Your heart is in the right place.

children.name: Text
children.value: May there be more good news from you.

children.name: Text
children.value: This cannot be allowed to harm our plans.

children.name: Text
children.value: We can find a way around this.

children.name: Text
children.value: I don't want to cut ties with you.

children.name: Text
children.value: Ask youself, whose side are you on?

children.name: Text
children.value: I am Isabel Sarmento and I will see my country freed. Are you with me or against me?

children.name: Text
children.value: I am Isabel Sarmento. Do not stand between me and my country's freedom!

children.name: Text
children.value: You are sure you weren't followed?

children.name: Text
children.value: Good to see a friendly face in these times.

children.name: Text
children.value: We're running low on everything, as usual.

children.name: Text
children.value: We search all our visitors -  a necessary precaution.

children.name: Text
children.value: Ready to evacuate at a moment's notice.

children.name: Text
children.value: We make do with what we have.

children.name: Text
children.value: I hope they'll remember this as the birthplace of a revolution.

children.name: Text
children.value: This is our new home now, we should be happy for that.

children.name: Text
children.value: We've got to be agile, ready to move at the drop of a hat.

children.name: Text
children.value: We can load up in a day, and be gone in a night.

children.name: Text
children.value: It's hard to get ships. We are lucky to have friends to help us.

children.name: Text
children.value: We never sink a ship if we can take it.

children.name: Text
children.value: I am so happy someone could help us.

children.name: Text
children.value: Words can't express how grateful we are.

children.name: Text
children.value: It is a risk worth taking.

children.name: Text
children.value: I'll join them again in the fields... my brothers and sisters, once we have set this land free.

children.name: Text
children.value: I was young when I joined the movement, I never imagined I would one day be giving the orders.

children.name: Text
children.value: This is not about revenge, but securing our people a future free of La Corona. We have to stick together.

children.name: Text
children.value: My brother fought back violently against La Corona. He was murdered. We have to try another way.

children.name: Text
children.value: If we strike against La Corona, we have to make it count!

children.name: Text
children.value: Jean is reckless like my brother was. I don't blame him. He is only trying to survive, to protect the ones he loves.

children.name: Text
children.value: Let Admiral Silva cling to his dying dream, we hear the little birds of freedom sing!

children.name: Text
children.value: La Corona may be our enemy, not the Queen, but to trust empire for us is impossible.

children.name: Text
children.value: If Anne could forget the past, we could build a better future together.

children.name: Text
children.value: Alonso is a powder keg. He threatens to destroy the delicate balance we've worked so hard for.

children.name: Text
children.value: Madame Kahina is the best. Quick, clean, and never draws attention. How does she do it?

children.name: Text
children.value: George dances well for an invalid, we all need to cut free sometimes.

children.name: Text
children.value: In future, keep your flagship intact, resources are scarce.

children.name: Text
children.value: There must be a better way.

children.name: Text
children.value: There is no time for this.

children.name: Text
children.value: This will not help our struggle.

children.name: Text
children.value: You steam ahead, my 'ands are oily.

children.name: Text
children.value: Something fer you to fiddle with.

children.name: Text
children.value: Shine yer blow lamp on this would'yer?

children.name: Text
children.value: If you don't exploit this, some other bird will.

children.name: Text
children.value: Go then, I got stuff to do.

children.name: Text
children.value: Fixed that up good, didn't yer.

children.name: Text
children.value: Nice juicy little oyster that is.

children.name: Text
children.value: Corrr yeah, just how I likes it.

children.name: Text
children.value: Didn't take you for a Janus-face, fair play to yer.

children.name: Text
children.value: You've left the whole thing a ruddy jumble!

children.name: Text
children.value: Well that's the nail in the coffin.

children.name: Text
children.value: Hurry or the flies'll start laying.

children.name: Text
children.value: Sit on a firework would yer?

children.name: Text
children.value: Got another lamp needs lighting n'all.

children.name: Text
children.value: Sputter on little engine, I'll keep you greased.

children.name: Text
children.value: Wonderful, but I've got another turkey for you to pluck.

children.name: Text
children.value: Old Nate can make double-cross worth your while.

children.name: Text
children.value: Want more? There is no more!

children.name: Text
children.value: Not even a morsel for yer.

children.name: Text
children.value: I'd be blown away, if not for me ropes…

children.name: Text
children.value: You make silk purses from sow's ears.

children.name: Text
children.value: Something always drops from the pipe with you.

children.name: Text
children.value: I've a bone to pick with you.

children.name: Text
children.value: Let me wipe me hand yer eminence. Turkey grease, see.

children.name: Text
children.value: You made a lucky find! I'm a goto for scrags and cut-offs, knick-knacks and gravy.

children.name: Text
children.value: Is it rag or is it bone you're wantin'?

children.name: Text
children.value: Eh? I'm trying to keep a low profile.

children.name: Text
children.value: I've a wealth o' parts, real odds and ends.

children.name: Text
children.value: You've got me by the Diri-giblets, whaddya want?

children.name: Text
children.value: You wouldn't be after a mountain of lint would ya?

children.name: Text
children.value: What's that I can smell on you, pickled eggs?

children.name: Text
children.value: Should hold together for a time.

children.name: Text
children.value: Soldiers had no use for the iron, all frozen such as they were.

children.name: Text
children.value: I scratched and scraped for this.

children.name: Text
children.value: I always dreamed of a little shack to call my own.

children.name: Text
children.value: She used to be a wreck, but you'd never guess.

children.name: Text
children.value: I put a lot o' graft into fixing her up.

children.name: Text
children.value: Made of sterner stuff— like boiled hooves.

children.name: Text
children.value: Then what we waitin' for, let's get stuck in.

children.name: Text
children.value: Semaphore stations'll soon be disused - there's a tip for old iron.

children.name: Text
children.value: Found an egg with a palace in it. Fixed the hinge and stuck it on the bow of my lady blimp.

children.name: Text
children.value: Zeppelins'll take off, you'll see. Soon they'll all want a piece of my lady blimp.

children.name: Text
children.value: Turn a greasy hat inside out, and it looks to 'ave been oiled purposely!

children.name: Text
children.value: Coffins make nice boats. But make sure the lid doesn't shut on you.

children.name: Text
children.value: Isabel's people are resistors, fighting for their Ohms.

children.name: Text
children.value: I could use George Smith's bath chair, once he's gone. Can't be long now can it?

children.name: Text
children.value: Archibald Blake commissioned the Queen a balloon, then he realised it was all a lot of hot air.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Queen may have snatched every last bit of land and sea, but I have the skies to meself.

children.name: Text
children.value: Alonso's good to follow at a distance; for all the leftovers.

children.name: Text
children.value: That windsock Willie still complaining? The lad doesn't know his luck.

children.name: Text
children.value: Don't dabble with Kahina, she's a lethal businesswoman.

children.name: Text
children.value: I offered Bente a place on my balloon, but she guffawed and called it cheating!

children.name: Text
children.value: Bit fer you, chunk for me.

children.name: Text
children.value: Some nice little slivers in there.

children.name: Text
children.value: Gorr, take me for an idiot?

children.name: Text
children.value: Well, it's time for me to move on. Until we meet again!

children.name: Text
children.value: You're going to need your best ship and crew, only for it to sink to the icy bottom! Hehehe.

children.name: Text
children.value: Terrible waste of human life of course, but don't let that stop you.

children.name: Text
children.value: And be sure to prepare for the final curtain while you're at it.

children.name: Text
children.value: You really do have quite the desire to depart don't ya? Well it's your funeral.

children.name: Text
children.value: Never mind, eh! At least you won't die a block of ice.

children.name: Text
children.value: Seems a long way to go to die, but you look ready for it.

children.name: Text
children.value: Take your time, won't make a difference to Sir John.

children.name: Text
children.value: Congratulations! You crossed seven seas for a wasteland!

children.name: Text
children.value: Couldn't even shoot yerself in the foot? Well I feel sorry for ya.

children.name: Text
children.value: The whole expedition's a failure. But we all know that teamwork drivel's a myth.

children.name: Text
children.value: See— never worth getting mixed up in other people's business.

children.name: Text
children.value: What a waste of time! Just goes to show, you can't rely on others.

children.name: Text
children.value: There's nothing up there but the  ruddy cold.

children.name: Text
children.value: Hoping this will keep your head above water? Not Arctic water it won't.

children.name: Text
children.value: Dunno why you're so desperate for your eyeballs to freeze.

children.name: Text
children.value: At best we'll be pulling stiffs out the ice like teeth.

children.name: Text
children.value: Like frostbite do ya? Botulism? Scurvy? Got that all to look forward to.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Arctic's no more than a mariner's graveyard. Ooh, hang fire...

children.name: Text
children.value: As we're here, we might ask the Inuits if they chanced upon any lost property...

children.name: Text
children.value: The equipment won't have decomposed like the cadavers.

children.name: Text
children.value: We've a responsibility to Sir John to gather up his valuables.

children.name: Text
children.value: Hard to feel the cold when you see a glint, ain't it? Hehe.

children.name: Text
children.value: Found nothing but emptiness, why isn't I surprised?

children.name: Text
children.value: The deeper we go, the more likely we find something really juicy.

children.name: Text
children.value: You want an Icebreaker, so we can get to the fancy stuff.

children.name: Text
children.value: Never know what you'll find inside, if you don't crack things open.

children.name: Text
children.value: Now we can finally see if Sir John bequeaths us owt shiny.

children.name: Text
children.value: You need to grow yourself some tusks, my walrus-friend, or we'll never snag the goodies.

children.name: Text
children.value: What d'you wanna help those old duffers for? Unless...you've sniffed summat out?

children.name: Text
children.value: I've heard the Arctic Council ships are plushly furnished.

children.name: Text
children.value: Shame they had to still be alive and we couldn't just help ourselves.

children.name: Text
children.value: As long as their pocket watches still tick we should try afresh.

children.name: Text
children.value: Never should o' come here, why do you think they call it a wasteland?

children.name: Text
children.value: Looks like we'll have to dig up Sir John Faithful's army o' the dead another day.

children.name: Text
children.value: Shame we couldn't find 'em, I was looking forward to expanding my collection of brass buttons.

children.name: Text
children.value: Lady Faithful's hopes to resurrect her marriage, but Sir John's got cold feet, hehehe.

children.name: Text
children.value: Ice might even have helped preserve the merchandise.

children.name: Text
children.value: I think we all know where Sir John Faithful is now, don't we? (he's dead)

children.name: Text
children.value: I know her old man’s long dead, but his lavish instruments won’t be, eh?

children.name: Text
children.value: Don't be afraid to see the frozen look as you frisk their corpses, you’ll get used to it.

children.name: Text
children.value: You can see a body a mile off out here, nice and exposed.

children.name: Text
children.value: Knowing those old toffs, they'd probably skin each other before they'd skin a seal.

children.name: Text
children.value: 'I 'spect there's a few nice bits and bobs suspended about the place.

children.name: Text
children.value: Can't always wait til things are dead y'know...

children.name: Text
children.value: No-one'll notice the odd body. If they're well-preserved, we could sell 'em for dissection.

children.name: Text
children.value: Can't believe how much an Inuit'll give ya for a tarnished spoon, hehe.

children.name: Text
children.value: I'd have come before, if I'd known how easy it is to fleece the locals.

children.name: Text
children.value: If you're looking for the Hades and Styx, you're going in the right direction, hehe.

children.name: Text
children.value: We can really milk this predicament for all it's got, as long as we're quiet.

children.name: Text
children.value: Two years in a blizzard probably doesn't do your skin much good, does it?

children.name: Text
children.value: Now, we don't want to look like we're only in it for the proceeds.

children.name: Text
children.value: Now we're onto something. Let's hope for a shipwreck!

children.name: Text
children.value: I hope those ships are stuck fast in the ice, free for the taking!

children.name: Text
children.value: Aren't you wondering what's left of them ships?

children.name: Text
children.value: Blimey, by foot!? This all looks very grim of a sudden, doesn't it?!

children.name: Text
children.value: Afraid? Never seen a real corpse?

children.name: Text
children.value: If Lady Faithful thinks they're still alive let's humour the poor woman's delusion shall we?

children.name: Text
children.value: Let's get to the bottom of this mystery, and what's become of 'em.

children.name: Text
children.value: You'd think you'd seen a ghost, what's frozen yer?

children.name: Text
children.value: Some of them live?! Brings a tear to an old man's eye.

children.name: Text
children.value: Why d'you have to fade away before the final payoff!

children.name: Text
children.value: Heavens what a name, no wonder their luck, eh?

children.name: Text
children.value: You seem drawn to death, that's why I stick to you like fishglue.

children.name: Text
children.value: This place is more indifferent to humankind than I am.

children.name: Text
children.value: Cast your eyes about for any tidbits in the snow.

children.name: Text
children.value: Lady Faithful's bewitched, she won't notice if we shuffle off for a bit.

children.name: Text
children.value: A place so curious must have its curiosities…

children.name: Text
children.value: What's all this endeavour of yours for?

children.name: Text
children.value: A lot of furry animals out here.

children.name: Text
children.value: These Inuit are a help though, aren't they?

children.name: Text
children.value: There are times even I give the dead their due.

children.name: Text
children.value: A sight to chill even someone as soulless as myself.

children.name: Text
children.value: I think we could all use a tot of hot brandy.

children.name: Text
children.value: Even I'd start to miss the sight of other beings out here.

children.name: Text
children.value: We've come to a place of solitude.

children.name: Text
children.value: I can't bear to watch you do this to yourself.

children.name: Text
children.value: We thought you would end icebound too, but for your icebreaker.

children.name: Text
children.value: You can count on that, heheh! The noble old dame belongs to one of the most prosperous families there is.

children.name: Text
children.value: Most likely all those poor mugs indulging her husband are drowned or chewing on their own bones, but like I said, where that much lucre's rolling in, I'll never be far behind! How's about you?

children.name: Text
children.value: Yeah, go on and help the old dame send even more ships to be lost in the nothingness. Looks like you finally found your captain Ahab.

children.name: Text
children.value: Meanwhile, I will set up me own little camp nearby. Just in case you need anything, Ishmael!

children.name: Text
children.value: So you're off to the icy marrow with the old dame, brrr. Don't get lost will yer, guv? You're me best customer!

children.name: Text
children.value: All those ships transmuting into ghosts. And then... silence.

children.name: Text
children.value: Don't want to become an ice pop like Lady Faithful's hubbie? Then stay clear from the ice.

children.name: Text
children.value: Imagine being so dim as to think an icebreaker could crack that icy mountain.

children.name: Text
children.value: Trusting an icebreaker is what got them icebound in the first place!

children.name: Text
children.value: Not even an icebreaker can get through that. But an airship...

children.name: Text
children.value: You're going to need an airship if you want to get past that wall of ice.

children.name: Text
children.value: Trust me, your only way in is from above.

children.name: Text
children.value: You want an airship, so we can get to the fancy stuff.

children.name: Text
children.value: Spread your wings, chick! Need a flying lesson?

children.name: Text
children.value: When you have an airship, the sky's —literally— the limit.

children.name: Text
children.value: What is it now, you have no gas? I can lend you some...
